\sum_{i=0}^{\infty} x^i = \dfrac1{1-x}
\dfrac{d}{dx}\left(\sum_{i=0}^{\infty} x^i \right) = \dfrac{d}{dx}\left(\dfrac1{1-x} \right)
\sum_{i=0}^{\infty} \dfrac{d (x^i)}{dx} = \dfrac1{(1-x)^2} \implies \sum_{i=0}^{\infty} i x^{i-1} = \dfrac1{(1-x)^2}
